1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,850
In hundreds of interviews with people at all levels, I've made this discovery.

2
00:00:05,040 --> 00:00:09,729
The bigger the person, the more apt he is to encourage you to talk.

3
00:00:09,840 --> 00:00:13,729
The smaller the person, the more apt he is to preach to you.

4
00:00:14,320 --> 00:00:17,170
Big people monopolize the listening.

5
00:00:17,440 --> 00:00:20,370
Small people monopolize the talking.

6
00:00:20,959 --> 00:00:22,529
Note this, also.

7
00:00:22,800 --> 00:00:29,890
Top-level leaders in all walks of life spend much more time requesting advice than they do in giving it.

8
00:00:30,320 --> 00:00:35,249
Before a top man makes a decision, he asks, How do you feel about it?

9
00:00:35,360 --> 00:00:36,769
What do you recommend?

10
00:00:36,959 --> 00:00:39,570
What would you do under these circumstances?

11
00:00:39,680 --> 00:00:41,570
How does this sound to you?

12
00:00:42,320 --> 00:00:43,810
Look at it this way.

13
00:00:44,080 --> 00:00:47,330
A leader is a decision-making human machine.

14
00:00:47,440 --> 00:00:51,810
Now, to manufacture anything, you've got to have raw material.

15
00:00:52,080 --> 00:00:58,529
In reaching creative decisions, the raw materials are the ideas and suggestions of others.

16
00:00:58,959 --> 00:01:03,009
Don't, of course, expect other people to give you ready-made solutions.

17
00:01:03,120 --> 00:01:06,290
That's not the primary reason for asking and listening.

18
00:01:06,719 --> 00:01:12,529
Ideas of others help to spark your own ideas, so your mind is more creative.

19
00:01:13,280 --> 00:01:19,170
Recently, I participated as a staff instructor in an executive management seminar.

20
00:01:19,440 --> 00:01:22,290
The seminar consisted of 12 sessions.

21
00:01:22,400 --> 00:01:28,769
One of the highlights of each meeting was a 15-minute discussion by one of the executives on the topic,

22
00:01:28,959 --> 00:01:32,610
How I Solved My Most Pressing Management Problem.

23
00:01:33,120 --> 00:01:40,209
At the ninth session, the executive whose turn it was, a vice president of a large milk processing company,

24
00:01:40,320 --> 00:01:41,570
did something different.

25
00:01:41,760 --> 00:01:46,769
Instead of telling how he had solved his problem, he announced his topic as,

26
00:01:46,959 --> 00:01:51,570
Needed, Help on Solving My Most Pressing Management Problem.

27
00:01:51,840 --> 00:01:57,170
He quickly outlined his problem and then asked the group for ideas on solving it.

28
00:01:57,520 --> 00:02:00,930
To be sure, he got a record of each idea suggested.

29
00:02:00,959 --> 00:02:05,170
He had a stenographer in the room, taking down everything that was said.

30
00:02:05,840 --> 00:02:10,370
Later I talked with this man and complimented him on his unique approach.

31
00:02:10,640 --> 00:02:14,610
His comment was, there are some very sharp men in this group.

32
00:02:14,719 --> 00:02:17,410
I just figured I'd harvest some ideas.

33
00:02:17,600 --> 00:02:24,690
There's a good possibility something someone said during that session may give me the clue I need to solve the problem.

34
00:02:25,360 --> 00:02:29,890
Note, this executive presented his problem, then listened.

35
00:02:30,080 --> 00:02:35,410
In so doing, he got some decision-making raw material, and as a side benefit,

36
00:02:35,520 --> 00:02:42,209
the other executives in the audience enjoyed the discussion, because it gave them the opportunity to take part.

37
00:02:43,360 --> 00:02:47,890
Successful businesses invest large sums in consumer research.

38
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:53,090
They ask people about the taste, quality, size, and appearance of a product.

